[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "20:12-21 The proud Syrians were beaten, and the despised Israelites were conquerors. The orders of the proud, drunken king disordered his troops, and prevented them from attacking the Israelites. Those that are most secure, are commonly least courageous. Ahab slew the Syrians with a great slaughter. God often makes one wicked man a scourge to another.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Pavilions - \"Booths\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 33:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " margin; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 23:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jonah 4:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The term seems to be properly applied to a stationary \"booth\" or \"hut,\" as distinguished from a moveable \"tent.\" On military expeditions, and especially in the case of a siege, such \"huts\" were naturally constructed to shelter the king and his chief officers. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "12. as he was drinking, he and the kings in the pavilions—booths made of branches of trees and brushwood; which were reared for kings in the camp, as they still are for Turkish pashas or agas in their expeditions [Keil].",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Set yourselves in array—Invest the city.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
